  "output": "Confirmed: this is a pure Python pipeline (fetchers → filters → SQLite store → notifiers), plus static HTML/PDF templates for CV generation — no React/frontend code exists anywhere in the repo, so that category is genuinely N/A here. Findings below are scoped to what's actually present.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job returned by a fetch run, `diff()` does a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With 125 configured sources and several boards paginating up to 40 pages (Amazon, Microsoft, Apple, ByteDance, Optiver, TwoSigma), a single run can push thousands of jobs through this loop — thousands of individual round trips to SQLite instead of a handful of batched statements.\n\n```python\n# current: 1 SELECT + 1 INSERT/UPDATE per job, in a Python loop\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nFix: fetch all existing hashes for the batch in one query, then use `executemany` for the writes:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(cur.execute(q, chunk).fetchall())\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append(row)\n        elif prev_hash != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append(row)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ..., :now, :now)\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n(`existing.update(cur.fetchall())` works because `row_factory=sqlite3.Row` rows unpack as 2-tuples when selecting exactly `key, content_hash`.)\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(include)` and `_compile(exclude)` on **every job**, recompiling the same keyword regexes from scratch each time. `filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job in a list comprehension, so for N jobs and M keywords you get O(N·M) regex compilations instead of O(M).\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include_re, exclude_re, locations, cutoff)]\n\n\ndef match(job: Job, include: list[re.Pattern], exclude: list[re.Pattern],\n          locations: list[str] | None, cutoff: datetime | None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nWith 125 sources this can easily be 5,000+ jobs per run — compiling the same 5-10 keyword patterns 5,000 times instead of once.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `Job.content_hash` computed twice per job\n\n`content_hash` (models.py:66-69) is a `@property` that runs `sha256` on every access. In the changed-job path, `Store.diff` calls `job.content_hash` once for the comparison, then `_insert`/`_update` call `job.to_row()`, which computes `content_hash` **again**. Cheap individually, but it's a double hash for every job, every run.\n\n`Job` is `@dataclass(slots=True)`, so `functools.cached_property` won't work directly (needs `__dict__`). Simplest fix: compute the row once in `diff()` and reuse it instead of recomputing inside `_insert`/`_update`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    ...\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}  # hash computed exactly once here\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, row)\n        elif prev_hash != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, row)\n        ...\n\ndef _insert(self, cur, row: dict) -> None:\n    cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ...)\", row)\n```\n\n## 4. Biggest caching opportunity — full board re-fetch every run, no conditional requests\n\n`sources.yaml` runs 125 sources every 12 hours (per your Twilio-notification commit). Several fetchers (`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_bytedance`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_workday`) paginate up to 20-40 pages **in full, every single run**, even though the boards are explicitly documented as sorted newest-first (see the Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix docstrings). The only \"stop early\" logic in each fetcher checks against an in-run `seen` set, not against what's already in `jobs.db` — so a board that hasn't changed since the last run still gets fully re-crawled.\n\nTwo concrete options:\n\n**a) Stop paginating once you hit an already-known job** (cheap, no HTTP-level caching needed — since these boards sort newest-first, once you see a `key` that's already in the store with the same content, everything after it is old news):\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_amazon(client, source, known_keys: set[str] | None = None) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    for pg in range(max_pages):\n        ...\n        fresh = [j for j in parse_amazon(company, jobs_raw) if j.external_id not in seen]\n        if not fresh:\n            break\n        seen.update(j.external_id for j in fresh)\n        jobs.extend(fresh)\n        if known_keys and all(j.key in known_keys for j in fresh):\n            break  # ran into a page of entirely-already-seen jobs; newer pages won't have anything new\n    return jobs\n```\n\nThis requires threading `store.conn` keys into `fetch_all`/`fetch_source`, which is a bigger structural change — worth doing if the 12h cron cost (network + wall time across 125 sources) matters, since it turns most runs from \"re-fetch entire board\" into \"fetch first page or two.\"\n\n**b) HTTP-level conditional GET** for the JSON-API fetchers (Greenhouse, Ashby, Lever, etc. all send `ETag`/`Last-Modified`) — cache the response and send `If-None-Match`, short-circuiting on 304. Lower payoff than (a) for the paginated bespoke boards since those don't send per-page ETags reliably, but essentially free for the `_simple()`-registered ATSes.\n\n## 5. Memory leaks / resource handling\n\nNo leaks found — `httpx.AsyncClient` is properly closed in `fetch_all`'s `finally` (fetchers.py:1016-1020), `Store` is used as a context manager everywhere it's called (`pipeline.py:42`, `agent.py:57-58`), and SMTP uses a `with` block (notify.py:69). Nothing to fix here.\n\n## Priority order\n\n1. **#4a (skip already-seen pages)** — highest leverage; cuts network calls and wall-clock time for the 12h scheduled run across the largest boards (Amazon/Microsoft/Apple run 40/40/10-page pagination caps).\n2. **#1 (batch the diff)** — matters once job volume is in the thousands per run, which it already is given 125 sources.\n3. **#2 (compile filters once)** — trivial fix, applies on every run regardless of scale.\n4. **#3 (dedupe the hash computation)** — minor, bundle with #1 since the same code path changes.\n",
